  "local_port": 49604,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Has anyone survived a plane crash?",
  "response": "Yes, many people have survived plane crashes. According to the National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB), the overall survival rate for aircraft accidents is around 95%. While plane crashes are often catastrophic, there have been numerous instances where passengers and crew members have survived due to a variety of factors, including the type of crash, the effectiveness of safety measures, and sheer luck.\n\nHere are a few notable examples of plane crash survivors:\n\n1. **US Airways Flight 1549 (Miracle on the Hudson) - 2009:**\n   - All 155 passengers and crew survived after the plane made an emergency landing in the Hudson River. The incident was largely attributed to the skill of the pilot, Captain Chesley \"Sully\" Sullenberger.\n\n2. **Air Canada Flight 143 (Gimli Glider) - 1983:**\n   - The plane ran out of fuel mid-flight due to a metric conversion error, but the pilots managed to glide the aircraft to a former air force base in Gimli, Manitoba. All 69 passengers and crew survived.\n\n3. **British Airways Flight 9 - 1982:**\n   - The plane flew through a cloud of volcanic ash, causing all four engines to fail. The pilots managed to restart the engines and land the plane safely. All 263 passengers and crew survived.\n\n4. **Ethiopian Airlines Flight 961 - 1996:**\n   - Hijackers forced the plane to run out of fuel, leading to a crash-landing off the coast of the Comoros Islands. Of the 175 people on board, 50 survived.\n\n5. **TACA Flight 110 - 1988:**\n   - The plane suffered a dual engine failure due to heavy rain and hail. The pilots managed to land the plane safely on a levee in Louisiana. All 45 passengers and crew survived.\n\nThese examples highlight that while plane crashes are terrifying and often deadly, survival is possible under the right circumstances.",
